05215nam a22007215i 9780292767867DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211983txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927678677 a10.7560/7036122doi  a(DE-B1597)588417  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a883.0100aApproaches to Homer /ced. by Cynthia W. Shelmerdine, Carl A. Rubino. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1983  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tOdysseus and the Cyclops: Who Is Who -- tOdyssean Temporality: Many (Re)Turns -- tVirtue, Folly, and Greek Etymology -- tMycenaean Greece and Homeric Reflections -- tReverberation and Mythology in the Iliad -- tHomer in Byzantium: John Tzetzes -- tOn the Death of Sarpedon -- tThe Economic Man -- tThe Nature of Homeric Morality -- tList of Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aModern Homeric scholarship is distinguished by a dazzling diversity of approaches. That diversity is brilliantly displayed in this volume, in which nine well-known classicists approach the Homeric poems from the various perspectives of archaeology, economic history, philosophy, literary criticism, linguistics, and Byzantine history. Several essays are primarily concerned with what the Homeric poems teach us about the past. Richard Hope Simpson, for example, reviews the controversy sparked by his and John F. Lazenby's 1970 argument that the Catalogue of Ships in the Iliad accurately reflects the geography of Mycenean Greece. Using archaeology as just one of his starting points, Gregory Nagy reflects upon the death and funeral of Sarpedon as described in the Iliad. Our understanding of the word áté is enhanced by E. D. Francis, who closely examines its prehistory. Norman Austin's elegant and original discussion of tone in the Odyssey's Cyclops tale is animated by both psychoanalytic theory and his work with two practitioners of optometric visual training. Writing of Odysseus, James M. Redfield dubs that hero "the economic man" and links certain tensions in the Odyssey to the actual economic concerns of Greece in the late eighth century BC. Both Ann L. T. Bergren and Mabel L. Lang concern themselves with problems of narrative in the Homeric epics. Like Hope Simpson, C. J. Rowe updates a controversy—in this instance, the many objections raised to Arthur Adkins' influential 1960 study of moral values in Homer. Gareth Morgan provides a fascinating glimpse of the Homeric scholarship of another day by focusing on the work of the astonishing John Tzetzes in twelfth-century Byzantium.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aAustin, Norman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergren, Ann L. T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrancis, E. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLang, Mabel L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Gareth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNagy, Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRedfield, James M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRowe, C. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRubino, Carl A, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRubino, Carl A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShelmerdine, Cynthia W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShelme